al rhetorical toolkits' of continuity and reconciliation that allow the court's reliance on the past to be unaccounted for. Uitz' rigorous analysis and extensive research makes this work an asset to legal scholars and practitioners alike.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jul 2022) 0aConstitutional history. 0aConstitutional law. 0aContrôle juridictionnel des loisxHistoire. 0aDroit constitutionnel. 0aHistoire constitutionnelle. 0aJudicial reviewxHistory. 7aLAW / Courts.2bisacsh  aConstitutional courts, Constitutional history, Constitutional law, Judiciary, Political philosophy.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCentral European University Press eBook-Package 2013-1998z978311078055040uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978615505373340uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9786155053733423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9786155053733/original  a978-3-11-078055-0  Central European University Press eBook-Package 2013-1998c1998d2013  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_LAEC  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_LAEC  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_ESTMALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aEBA_STMALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA12STME  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA18STMEE  aPDA5EBK